He rarely uses a pot.
Degei lives in a wooden building in Enarotal, the capital of the Paniai region, located in the restless province of Papua, Indonesia. When he prepares dinner, he usually puts the sweet potato — locally —nota — directly into the fireplace.
After half an hour, the sweet potato burned on the carrion is eaten grumblingly with bare, unwashed hands.
Degei's home has no furniture. He sits on a muddy ground floor, where he usually also takes care of his daily chores, such as washing laundry in cloudy water fetched from a nearby swamp.
The toilet office is supplied by a bucket in a roofless room.
Degei is the youngest of her husband's four wives, and has not been assigned fields to care for.
Polygamy is common here.
Working late can be dangerous: most of the men in the village are unemployed, and many drink a lot, and soldiers must also be taken into account.
“No one dares to walk in the village after 5 p.m.,” Degei said.
This is a rare peek into everyday life in the Papua Highlands, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969. The annexation was preceded by a controversial referendum, in which 1,026 village elders were forced to vote publicly in front of the occupying forces.
The local independence movement, which opposed Dutch power, quickly turned its anger on the Jakarta government, which strictly controls the region and prevents foreign journalists and human rights observers from entering it.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua. The eastern part of the island belongs to Papua New Guinea.
Enarotali is remote and turbulent. The journey starts with an hour and a half flight from the provincial capital Jayapura to Nabire and continues on a stomach-wrenching five-hour drive with a rental car.
There's no public transportation here.
The town of about 19,000 people has wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, whose corrugated roofs have been dyed yellowish brown by rust.
Few Indonesians have been here, not to mention journalists and foreigners.
Before the arrival of Christian missionaries, the Papuan Mee Pago tribes worshiped the god Uga Tamee.
There have been other changes.
“We didn’t have any clothes like this,” Degei says. He means a colorful hand woven wrap hat, a dark skirt and a bright-colored blouse.
We used to only have magazines covered in our bodies.
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, with 28% of its population living below the poverty line, and child mortality and illiteracy are among the highest in Asia.
But it is also the gold country of Indonesia.
Paniai is about the size of New Jersey, with a population of 153,000. Only about a hundred kilometers from Paniai is Grasberg, the largest and most lucrative gold mine in the world. It is owned by Freeport McMoran, a company based in Phoenix, United States.
In 2015, the mine generated $3.1 billion in gold and copper for Freeport.
In addition, Papua has an estimated $78 billion in wood reserves.
For the Papuans, however, these riches bring misery because they mean the suffocating presence of a strong Indonesian army.
In 2005, the New York Times revealed that Freeport paid local military personnel and military local units nearly $20 million between 1998 and 2004, with individual officers paid as much as $150,000.
Papua's demands for greater self-determination threaten this source of income and are mercilessly silenced.
According to human rights activists, since 1969, the Indonesian army has killed more than 500,000 people and raped, tortured and imprisoned thousands.
According to the Asian Human Rights Commission, mass killings in the highlands of the Papuan tribes in the 1970s gained proportions of genocide.
Last year, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 people in the area in peaceful protests.
Brisbane Archdiocese's 2016 report We Will Lose Everything reports on previous year's atrocities, such as executions without trial, torture - rape and electrocution are particularly popular means - and relentless attacks on peaceful protests.
“It’s hard to count the number of victims because there are cases every week,” said Andreas Harsono, an Indonesian researcher for Human Rights Watch.
The screw has been tightened as Papua's natural resources attract migrants from other parts of Indonesia.
Of the 3.5 million inhabitants of the province, 83 percent are Christians, but the demographic structure is changing as Indonesian populous islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi migrate to the region in search of a better livelihood.
