Red meat, dairy products and chocolate may relieve irritable bowel syndrome
Red meat and chocolate may sound like nightmares of the digestive system.
However, a recent study claims the opposite: a diet rich in meat protein and dairy products may ease irritable bowel syndrome.
Irritable bowel syndrome is an incurable disease that affects about 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 people in the UK. It causes abdominal cramps, swelling, recurrent or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
However, researchers at the University of Washington found that the essential amino acid tryptophan contained in the protein helps the body develop immune cells that strengthen bowel resilience.
Marco Colonna, director of the study, said immune cells guarded the swamp and ensured that harmful microbes hiding in the food did not enter the body.
Cells that balance cells that cause inflammation, which strengthen resilience, protect the body without damaging sensitive tissues.
If the balance falls too close to the inflammation, the result may be irritable bowel syndrome.
The studies found that immune cells that strengthen tolerance are present in mice with a specific bacteria in their intestines.
This bacteria needs tryptophan to make immune cells appear. Tryptophan is one of the building blocks of proteins.
“We found a link between Lactobacillus reuteri and the development of cells that promote resilience. Lactobacillus reuteri is part of the normal gut microbiome,” says Professor Colonna.
The more tryptophan in the diet of mice, the more such immune cells they had.
If the same works in humans, the combination of Lactobacillus reuteri and a diet rich in tryptophan can strengthen intestinal resilience and reduce inflammation sensitivity.
In the study of immune cells that strengthen tolerance, the postdoctoral researcher Luisa Cervantes-Barragan found that although one group of mice had such cells, they were not found in mice of the same species, which were kept separate from the other group.
He suspected that the difference was related to the microbiome of the mice' intestines, i.e. the normal community of bacteria, fungi and viruses in the digestive tract.
When the intestinal DNA of mice was examined, six species of bacteria were observed in mice with immune cells but not in other mice.
When Lactobacillus reuteri was administered to mice in a sterile environment without intestinal microbiome and without developing immune cells, immune cells began to appear.
The researchers wanted to find out how bacteria affect the immune system. They grew Lactobacillus reuter bacteria in the liquid and transferred small amounts of fluids — without bacteria — to immature immune cells isolated from mice.
Immune cells developed into tolerant cells.
When the active ingredient was purified from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of tryptophan metabolism known as indole-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the diet of mice, the number of tolerance cells increased by about 50 percent. When tryptophan was halved, the number of cells decreased by half from the previous one.
According to Cervantes-Barragan, humans have the same resistance cells as mice, and most of us have Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in our digestive tract.
It is not yet known whether tryptophan by-products from Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria cause cells to develop in humans in the same way as in mice. However, genetic defects associated with tryptophan have been observed in people with Irritable bowel syndrome.
“We probably want to promote the development of such cells because they regulate inflammation on the inner surfaces of the intestines,” Cervantes-Barragan said.
High tryptophan levels combined with Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria may contribute to their generalisation.
