White House exhibit cost thousands of dollars to taxpayers
The White House's decision last month to fly a naval helicopter to the southern lawn of the White House for an American production event cost taxpayers $24,000, according to military documents received by TIME magazine.
The green-white Sikorsky VH-3D helicopter is referred to as Marine One when the president is on board. It was a attraction at an event at the White House on 17 July 2017 that featured American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and a group of White House officials were introduced to the products from all 50 states.
In addition to a helicopter made in Connecticut, a sailboat from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a truck from Mississippi were exhibited.
The White House military office had requested a helicopter station by mission order only about 36 hours before its landing on the southern lawn field — an exceptional one — for the event. This is evident from the documents of the naval HMX-1 helicopter squadron.
“I just wanted to make sure that you were aware of it because it was an exceptional event that got a lot of visibility — on the day before the event, the HMX-1 unit commander wrote in an e-mail to his superior, who is the deputy commandant of the Navy Air Force.
The message said that the helicopter would arrive on the southern lawn field at 17 July seven o'clock in the morning and the event would start at three o'clock in the afternoon. The helicopter would not leave the site until after the lawn field was emptied between six and nine o'clock in the evening.
In addition, the message stated that if a helicopter was delayed to leave the White House, another crew would be needed due to service time constraints.
The original crew was in the helicopter during the event, and the unit's security personnel were at the helicopter when it was on the ground.
It is not clear from the documents received by TIME magazine whether a second crew was eventually needed.
The U.S. Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using state property for political purposes.
According to the documents, HMX-1 inquired whether the incident was a violation of the law.
“One of our questions was whether this was a breach of the Hatch Act, and we were told that there was no breach,” the commander wrote.
“It sounds like you can participate,” replied the assistant commandant.
Made in America was the official White House event, so it was not covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political nuances.
In the event, the president spoke in favour of the health reform that had been before the Senate at the time, as well as looser state regulation.
The use of the Marine One helicopter and the Air Force One aircraft for political purposes is not a new phenomenon.
Presidents must use them on their journeys,
But using them only for photos is unusual.
Trump's actions attracted attention in February when Air Force One rolled behind the presidential campaign event in Melbourne, Florida. Trump has strongly criticized the use of his predecessor's presidential aircraft on Twitter.
“The White House is very pleased with the Made in America event, which featured products made by American workers from all 50 states,” White House press secretary Lindsay Walters said.
HMX-1 crews regularly conduct training flights in the Washington area and train to bring the president to the White House with centimeters accuracy.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 made 58 training landings for the White House.
According to one official, flights to Made in America included a monthly training quota for the crew.
The unit's helicopters were also flown 11 hours that day in non-presidential support missions.
According to the White House, the incident did not entail any additional costs for taxpayers.
Sikorsky's spokesperson said the company was not involved in organizing a helicopter demonstration on the southern lawn of the White House.
HMX-1 has no record of flights related to Presidential duties, and it is difficult to accurately estimate the costs of the event.
According to the Ministry of Defence’s 2017 hourly compensation, the compensation level for the VH-3D helicopter is $24,380 per flight hour.
According to HMX-1 documents, flights from Quantico Base to and from the State of Virginia to the White House lasted for a total of an hour.
According to the White House, the operating costs of the helicopter are significantly lower.
“The calculation of the cost to taxpayers according to the level of compensation is misleading,” Walters said.
The estimated level of compensation includes staff, maintenance and many other so-called embedded costs, which are taken into account in the annual appropriations.
According to a 2015 RAND study, compensation levels do not include personnel costs, but take into account fuel, maintenance and contract costs.
At the time of the event, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of the helicopter in the event.
“The idea is to introduce American production,” Spicer said.
“I know Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud to be involved in ensuring national security and employing hundreds or thousands of people.
And I think, like most Americans, we are proud of the helicopter and other defense equipment that many Americans have worked hard for.
It is perfectly appropriate to point out...
It is not certain whether Trump was on a helicopter during the event, but at least he sat in the driver's seat.
